<span id="freeTextContainer821671969377050667">Put aside at pg 172 but not quite ready to abandon and have no idea when or if I&apos;ll return to it. Lovely writing but old-old, hate to say but almost stale Irish story of IRA &quot;ghosts.&quot; Deane&apos;s language makes it fairly fresh, but not enough to keep me going. Problem is I&apos;ve read so much Irish lit, past and present, on the same subject, and it becomes like reading yet another work on evil legacy of American slavery: there&apos;s Morrison&apos;s Beloved and there&apos;s everything else. And Deane, though talented,</span>
  <span id="freeText821671969377050667" style="display:none">Put aside at pg 172 but not quite ready to abandon and have no idea when or if I'll return to it. Lovely writing but old-old, hate to say but almost stale Irish story of IRA "ghosts." Deane's language makes it fairly fresh, but not enough to keep me going. Problem is I've read so much Irish lit, past and present, on the same subject, and it becomes like reading yet another work on evil legacy of American slavery: there's Morrison's Beloved and there's everything else. And Deane, though talented, is no Morrison. Maybe not quite "everything else," but just too familiar to keep me engaged right now. </span>
