<div id="review_2081984600" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2081984600" />
    <a title="Tina Tamman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/36862800-tina-tamman"><img alt="Tina Tamman" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1424034377p2/36862800.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2081984600?book_show_action=true">Aug 11, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tina Tamman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tina Tamman" href="/user/show/36862800-tina-tamman">Tina Tamman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/36862800-tina-tamman?shelf=book-club">book-club</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2081984600" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13102910443505335650">This is a difficult book to like. I have a lot of sympathy for Ireland, like most Irish writing, but I rebel at the structure of this particular novel. For a long time I wasn&apos;t even sure it was a novel at all; it seemed more like a memoir, episodic in style. And at one point I found it quite so boring that I decided to go and clean the bathroom instead. However, it&apos;s our next read in the book club, so I had to press on. And now I&apos;ve read it all. Admittedly, it did get more interesting towards th</span>
  <span id="freeText13102910443505335650" style="display:none">This is a difficult book to like. I have a lot of sympathy for Ireland, like most Irish writing, but I rebel at the structure of this particular novel. For a long time I wasn't even sure it was a novel at all; it seemed more like a memoir, episodic in style. And at one point I found it quite so boring that I decided to go and clean the bathroom instead. However, it's our next read in the book club, so I had to press on. And now I've read it all. Admittedly, it did get more interesting towards the end when I began to understand what it was all about.<br />The failure of the book is that I don't feel anything for any of the characters. For a start, they are numerous. Not having any brothers or sisters myself, let alone cousins or nephews or aunts or uncles, I felt quite lost when Ena, for example, died. Who was Ena? And so on.<br />The title, I have to admit, is quite clever.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13102910443505335650" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


