    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2871362381" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2871362381" />
    <a title="Loretto Leary" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22343021-loretto-leary"><img alt="Loretto Leary" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1374243186p2/22343021.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2871362381?book_show_action=true">Jun 25, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Loretto Leary" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Loretto Leary" href="/user/show/22343021-loretto-leary">Loretto Leary</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2871362381" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15198834310325817399">Although I would give this book five stars for the writing style, elegant and carefully honed, I think I’d award it four stars for the story itself. The finer nuances of the novel will be lost on broader audiences who seem to devour crap like Fifty Shades of Gray and spur tales like this because the readers lack the patience to allow the story to reveal itself. The slow reveal is a literary device manipulated by Deane with skill here.<br/><br/>Irish people with a love of the past and those (any nationalit</span>
  <span id="freeText15198834310325817399" style="display:none">Although I would give this book five stars for the writing style, elegant and carefully honed, I think I’d award it four stars for the story itself. The finer nuances of the novel will be lost on broader audiences who seem to devour crap like Fifty Shades of Gray and spur tales like this because the readers lack the patience to allow the story to reveal itself. The slow reveal is a literary device manipulated by Deane with skill here.<br /><br />Irish people with a love of the past and those (any nationality) with an appreciation for memoir told in densely poetic prose with keen and vivid imagery will also like this book. If you are that rare person, then this book is a must-read. <br /><br />Much akin to John Banville’s The Sea, the nuanced tale and slow reveal is worth the wait. But wait you will, as you traverse through cavernous memories layered with mythologies that are linked to real events, as you try to figure out why this family seems to struggle with their past and steer clear of all controversies in the present: a hard thing to do in the North of Ireland in 1940s and ’50s. All is revealed to both the narrator and the reader at the same time. We are, essentially, unraveling the mystery and discovering the truth with him about what really happened to his Uncle Eddie and his Uncle by marriage, McIlhenny.<br /><br />Reading in the Dark, aptly titled I might add, deals with secrets. However, even deeper than that it deals with the prized Irish notion of respectability, the successful divide and conquer campaign of the British Empire, fostering distrust among the community, growing frustration for vagueness, the safety of keeping out of the way political issues in the north, the difficulty of staying out of political issues in the north, inherited family traumas, mental illness caused by overwhelming guilt, death, informers, and the power of the Catholic Church in Ireland.<br /><br />The Feud is a chapter that stands out for me. Not only does it show the land grabbing mentality that the Irish used to get one rung higher on the social ladder, but it also demonstrated that no one was watching for the care of young people. Land, ownership of land, and having more “things” it is at the crux of all family feuds and this was a big one. Making the girls eat margarine instead of butter for most readers, would not be a big deal in other countries, but in Ireland, it was a HUGE insult. Margarine wasn't real food, it was cheap and tasted like crap. That part struck me as being authentic and I trusted the narrator because of the telling of it.<br /><br />The Chapter entitled Roses was frustrating. Unable to articulate his frustrations with his parents and their anger at him for drawing the police on them about the bullying incident, the narrator destroys the rose bushes. I needed a reason for this. The story is told with an older voice and the lack of reason for this behavior was frustrating for me. I felt that the explanation didn't have to be explicit, but the subtle "hinting at" technique which is handled so beautifully elsewhere seems to have been abandoned in this chapter, but deftly handled in the chapter entitled, Field of the Disappeared. However, the scene with the father at the end of this chapter (Roses) is just lovely. Teaching the narrator an important lesson wasn’t easy but it had to be done for his own good.<br /><br />The final chapter made me feel sorry for the mother, a woman haunted by ghosts of the mind. All along I thought she was just an eccentric, possibly even clairvoyant if you believe in that sort of thing, but in the final chapter, you realize that a very simple mistake, one that was meant to save a life, ended up affecting the whole extended family. <br /><br />The British father showing up at their doorstep to find out how his son died was heartbreaking but felt a little contrived. I felt the last few chapters were rushed, while other chapters dragged on. I had a real issue with how much of the Anglican Ministers lecture about the bombing campaign could be recalled by the narrator. Almost too much. The teacher summed it up perfectly, that would have been enough. <br /><br />I would recommend this book, but it is Literary Prose and the language, although beautiful and poetic, may put off some readers who just want to hear a tale of family misfortune and a narrator’s growing appreciation for his parents and their numerous attempts to raise children in a hostile environment. <br />The mother’s mental break down and the fun of Aunt Katie’s arrival is quite surprising. His mother’s family seem to be steeped in superstition. The story about the children who change was actually a stand-alone story. I really enjoyed it. <br /><br />It is a book of secrets held onto tightly in an effort to keep the family respectable. It's a hard battle to keep those secrets from the people who inherit them and live in a community who knows their past. Between the secret of the family feud, Uncle Eddie, the mother's illness, IRA informants, and sexual awakenings ridden with Catholic guilt, there is nothing new here except the beautiful prose and the unraveling, albeit slow, of a worthwhile read for those patient enough to stick with it. My advice, stick with it. </span>
  <a data-text-id="15198834310325817399" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


