  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3233505763" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3233505763" />
    <a title="Heather" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10738912-heather"><img alt="Heather" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1587571845p2/10738912.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3233505763?book_show_action=true">Mar 19, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Heather" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Heather" href="/user/show/10738912-heather">Heather</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3233505763" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2474952443993003451">I loved everything about Reading in the Dark! I won&apos;t write too much as I cannot spoil this read for anyone. You must discover its secrets as our unnamed boy learns them. Told in the first person, each chapter is a vignette of an Irish Catholic boy&apos;s life, (3rd oldest of 7 children), from February 1945 until July 1971. Our boy is desperately trying to understand the aforementioned mystery running throughout the novel. A mystery contained in the family feuds, secrets, and gossip of every small to</span>
  <span id="freeText2474952443993003451" style="display:none">I loved everything about Reading in the Dark! I won't write too much as I cannot spoil this read for anyone. You must discover its secrets as our unnamed boy learns them. Told in the first person, each chapter is a vignette of an Irish Catholic boy's life, (3rd oldest of 7 children), from February 1945 until July 1971. Our boy is desperately trying to understand the aforementioned mystery running throughout the novel. A mystery contained in the family feuds, secrets, and gossip of every small town but Seamus Deane also blesses us with Irish folklore and legend. <br /><br />Every character has so many layers and is wonderful. On the surface, these are simple stories of a family. But, families bring out the best and worst in us. The people within are flawed -- some more than others. Within this family microcosm, there are some heavy topics -- mental health, child welfare, politics, war, greed, pride, prejudice, religion, justice. There are huge unkindnesses, some by significant family members. Underneath it all is love but a love that changes and matures. It is a weighty story and not always a feel good one. Actually, my feelings ran the gamut! I laughed. I cried. I was horrified. I was incredulous. I couldn't understand some characters' decisions. Some characters grew on me throughout my read. As per every family, there are no happy endings. There's just a life -- and it's complicated.<br /><br />P.S. The accounts of his education with the Catholic priests was everything! One priest in particular, Father Gildea, warrants his own book:<br /><br />"'Mental algebra. Ground rules. Well-known, but must be repeated, first for the sake of the brain-dead and the memory-less, who are in the usual staggering majority; but who take a litigant's pleasure in claiming that they are not clear. I lie awake at night, imagining for these creatures a condign punishment; yet I have failed. Does this bespeak in me a failure of imagination, or in them an unanswerable corruption?'" <br /><br />And a little later on, when one of the boys calls him sir:<br /><br />"'Sir? Sir? Have I altered in appearance? Has my Roman collar become a tie, my soutane a suit of mouldy tweed?'"<br /><br />Brilliant :) Seamus Deane, I must read another!!</span>
  <a data-text-id="2474952443993003451" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


